# Spatial Offline Report Crafter

## Purpose
This AI agent template is intended for workflows where a client provides spatial data and needs to ingest multiple files from field staff in a semi-structured format.

Run each phase with specific paths to your data. Ensure everything for a phase is complete before proceeding to the next phase prompts.

## Report Generation Dependency
- HTML and DOCX report scripts live in a separate reusable git project:  
  https://github.com/GetBack2Basics/Spatial_Report_Crafter.git and https://github.com/GetBack2Basics/Spatial_Document-Crafter
- Use this report project after creating the review GPKG to produce client-ready outputs.
- Required review GPKG layers:
  - `*_new_review`
  - `*_drift_review`
  - `*_displacement_vector`
- Recommended columns (see existing and depending on input):
  - `Asset_ID` or `asset_id`
  - `Drift_m`
  - `Risk_Level`
  - `Review_PotentialChange`
  - `Review_Status`
  - `Src_CSV`
  - `Src_Type`
  - `Src_Date`
  - `Src_Value`
  - `Comments`
- Call report scripts directly from their installed/cloned paths: see md files in project for details.
## GIS Data Workflow Phases

### Phase 1: Discover
- Inspect source folder structure.
- Identify domains and file formats.
- Read sample records and check geometry columns.
- Validate geometry types match expected assets (points/lines/polygons).
- If endpoint access is required: probe a sample first; if it fails, inform the user and stop before bulk operations.
- Summarise findings: count, formats, geometry status, and data-quality red flags.
- **Ask user:** agree on source inventory and domain scope before proceeding.

### Phase 2: Scope & Design
- Propose review fields and classification rules with the user.
- Define drift threshold, attribute comparison columns, and status flags.
- Agree on review GPKG layer names and symbology categories.
- Agree on output paths and target write-back locations.
- Confirm no source/original files will be modified unless explicitly requested.
- **Ask user:** approve scope before writing any scripts.

### Phase 3: Prepare & Validate
- Write all scripts needed for the workflow (ingest, clean, match, build outputs into review GPKG).
- Stop for user review of scripts and paths.
- Do not run pipelines yet.
- Fix small issues flagged by the user inline.
- **Ask user:** approve script batch before execution.

### Phase 4: Execute
- Run ingestion and cleaning scripts.
- Generate review GPKG with classified features and flags.
- Build reports and maps using the report project scripts against the review GPKG.
- If any step returns zero features or unexpected nulls, halt and report.
- **Ask user after each major step:** review output counts and samples before continuing.

### Phase 5: Review & Iterate
- Present findings: new assets, drift counts, flagged records, and displacement vectors using generated HTML and DOCX reports.
- Highlight data-quality issues found.
- Make small fixes if the user requests.
- Regenerate outputs if logic changed.
- **Ask user:** confirm analysis output before write-back or final report.

### Phase 6: Commit & Document
- Run write-back dry-run and show diff.
- Only after approval: run commit write-back.
- Regenerate final report if needed.
- Document run parameters, counts, and thresholds used.
- **Ask user:** green light for production ingestion or archive instead.

## General Rules (All Phases)
- Use safe field expressions; avoid non-existent functions.
- Match field lengths to source or trim explicitly.
- Never modify files outside the designated working directory without permission.
- Probe external endpoints before depending on them.
- Verify geometry column names from actual source; do not assume defaults.
- Keep outputs separate from inputs until user approves write-back.
- Ask only when blocked or when a decision is required; otherwise execute, fix small issues, then report.
- For HTML reports, keep native folium basemap controls; only post-process for metadata links and custom WMS form.
- For DOCX reports, use native document format with structured tables and summary sections.
